segments.text: 22 years, do you recall much statistical similarity between those who were admitted with high scores, well, with their admission criterion and status, and their performance at A&M?
I think we'd have to go into the
measurement and research services to figure out.
I do think I recall that those who were admitted with the best academic and test scores probably came out better as far as the grade point average is concerned.
Many of them who were admitted with not as strong an academic record probably had to work harder at it
and probably graduated.

We still, we hear the tale, though, that as far as successful graduates, oftentimes those who graduated with the highest grade point average, they go more into research and writings and things like this, where those with a somewhat lesser, although not necessarily the bottom, but they perform more of the managerial functions and more of the

day-to-day operations and most many of the ones are very successful financially have been those who have learned to work hard while they were going to school I think all right let's make believe now that we have hired you as a consultant to Texas A&M to advise them

about admissions process and criterion based on your experience what would you advise them what process would you advise and what factors would you advise them to consider well i would have to assume first if you're going to do something like this that you've probably got a limited number of freshmen that you would want to enroll and of course what you want to do is get those who
you think would be the most successful or most likely to complete the curriculum in probably prescribed, quote, four-year time?
I think you've got to have some basic things which you want to look at.
I think that the academic performance of the student is certainly probably the best criteria that you'd want to, that we have.
In addition to this, scores which they make on standardized tests are useful in making your prediction.
I think you would also want to look at the type of activities a student participated in in high school.

whether it be in athletics or whether it be in student government, whether it be in the arts such as the band or orchestra, whether they had extracurricular activities within the community, whether they belong to certain type of church organizations, all these kinds of participation.
Sometimes their ethnic background may give you a key as to why they did or did not perform as well as they did.
I think it boils down to if you really want to select those students who may be best able to profit by the education, that you're going to have to do a
review, an individual review.
I don't think you can do it just on giving weighted points to various and certain aspects of the thing.
If you can throw in an interview I think it's even better.
Who should be present at that interview other than the prospective student?
It would probably be better if an admissions
counselor, the person who's dealing with and used to dealing with the admissions, and possibly some other person from maybe an academic area might be.
What about from the student's family?
Anybody?
Sometimes the students prefer to
talk without parents there.
Are you saying it's better without the parents?
I think it's probably better without the parents, for the most part.
Sometimes an interview with the parents without the student gives you some insight, too.
Again, we're talking about how much time you're able to spend in the selection process.
And the more time you can spend up to a certain point, probably the better job you can do.
I think part of the concern which we've always felt

was that many of our decisions had to be made in a very quick time because of the number of students we were dealing with, the fact that all students couldn't get in for interviews, and these kinds of things.
And it sometimes gave me concern that we just didn't have as much data as we'd like to have, and we're doing it on the, that we obviously, we may be overlooking
some factors in a student's life that might be very beneficial in making the selection.
Which is more important, the score in the verbal or the mathematical?
Statistically, the verbal score is more important.
And the selection criteria they used to use for the National Merit Scholars was weighted that way, I think, too.
Is there anything in this perfect setting for admissions review?
Should there be anything that the student submits other than transcript, an essay, or anything else?
Well, an essay would allow them to give you some additional information about them.
It also gives you a chance to make some kind of a judgment as to their writing abilities and these kind of things, which are going to be important when they get to the university.
Right.
And in this perfect admissions process, there would be an appeals opportunity or not?
We did have here, and I would always like to have an appeals process, yeah.
Because it gives those people, first place, I think, if they're really interested, they may make more of an effort in an appeal.
Who would be on the appeals panel?
Oh, I'd probably want at least three different people.
One an admissions person, probably somebody from outside the admissions office might look at it from a, just a, from the process,

From a time standpoint, it's sometimes a whole lot easier to have three different people from the admissions area look at it, although I think, again, sometimes somebody from outside the office may have a different set of glasses to look at than we might have.
We may sometimes get too focused in what we're looking at.
All right.
Now, again, relying on your experience, based on your experience, do you think A&M...
changed his admission requirements at about the right time and with about the same amount of restriction that they should have?
Well, I can remember back in the early 70s when Dr. Williams was here at a meeting one time, he made a comment that he thought 20,000 would be a nice size university.
And I certainly agreed with him as far as that's concerned.
However, we, because of our
popularity, I guess you'd say, we never even slowed down to 20,000.
I think that we probably started limiting the enrollment, it's hard to say, maybe a little bit late.
I don't know what the proper figure should be.
From a financial standpoint, looking at it from a tax base standpoint, I think that the people in Texas
have a right to expect the best from their educational institutions.
There are institutions in the state which I am told could probably handle more students at a lower cost.
And while this may say, well, you're being elitist, maybe,

I think that there are some schools that can do a very good job of educating students at a bachelor's level, which would allow more resources at the master's and doctor's level for some of the larger universities to fill that gap on the thing, where if they've got to spend the money educating more undergraduates, then there's less at other levels.
It's a matter of economics, I think.
Obviously, being an Aggie, I would think everybody ought to be an Aggie, but the university
From a personal standpoint, I think it has gotten so large that it's hard to have the personal interest in the students that you have when the enrollment is not quite as large.
Let's go back chronologically now.
Dr. Williams, the president, Calhoun, the vice president, in the 70s, and did they...
interfere with admissions?
Did they nitpick?
Or did you feel you had pretty clear understanding of what you all were to do, and you seldom, if ever, got anything overruled?
I don't recall that they ever
quote, overruled us in that sense.
They sometimes ask us to make admissions where the student had not met the stated criteria, but because of other factors they felt like the student might have a chance to be successful, I think.
About how often?
Very seldom.
Once a year?
I would say probably twice or three times a year, but again, just wild guess.
All right, then in 1976, Dr. Miller becomes the president, and Dr. Williams moves up to be chancellor.
Were there any changes in the process then?
Not really.
I think by that time, and again, as I recall, we were probably getting more crowded.
We were probably getting more requests to make exceptions, I think.
I think that we had...
More requests from possibly board members which were receiving input from people who lived and knew them and this kind of thing.
So I think it probably as time went on, as we raised the requirements some, as we had more students wanting to get in, I think we probably had more appeals.
And we probably made a few more exceptions at that time than we did other times.
Do you remember any that were bothersome?
To be honest, I think most times when certain board members got involved, it became bothersome because they seldom, as I recall, asked to see if it were in a student's interest to be admitted.
I think they were more concerned about getting a student admitted.
That's looking back at it.
If the board member wanted it done, whom did the board member normally contact here?
We had a few board members who would call Ed or I one direct.
For the most part,

president and I don't know that Dr. Vandiver or Dr. Miller set it up for that they would come through the board secretary so we had some kind of control over it and then that queries either to my office or to the president's office so getting getting the board not calling directly but at least through the board secretary and then
At some time, then that board secretary was directed to the president's office or to the vice president, Dr. Prescott, or to you or to someone else.
Now, when were those communications normally oral or in writing?
Not in the oral.
Were you at the commencement in the spring of 1980 when Dr. Miller did not shake hands with a graduate?
Yes.
Okay.
Describe, as you recall, what happened at the end of that.
Because she's the last degree recipient at the last of three commencements, Friday afternoon, Friday night, Saturday morning.
Because her name began with Z, and you graduate alphabetically by college and by major, and she was in biomedical science and veterinary medicine.
Her name was Melanie Zintgraff.
Describe, as you recall, what happened.
Well, the only, by that time, we had looked at several hundred students coming across the state and shaking hands and getting their diploma and everything.
And the only thing I remember about it, ask her, was the fact that when she got her diploma, he didn't shake her hand, which I thought was strange at the time.
Were you up where you could see what happened?

Yeah, at each of the Commencements, as you may recall, I was one of the, we led the faculty in, and I was always sitting on the stage because at that time, we were not handing out hoods at that time, they were carrying hoods, but anyway, I was always sitting on the stage because I had been leading the faculty in, so I was sitting on the stage and glanced over
I usually would watch them as they got their diplomas.
I do recall that he did check her hands.
All right.
As I recall, as dean of faculties, I would carry the mace, put it in the holder, go to the back of the stage.
Lieutenant Governor Bill Hobby was our commencement speaker.
And while they're passing out diplomas, he motioned for me to come up and sit near him.
And we were talking about my going out to UTEP to be the president.
And as I realized we were about to finish, I started to get out of my chair, and I heard some hissing, particularly from corps members.
And he asked, what is that all about?
And I said, well, they're unhappy about something.
And I looked around, and then I recognized who it was.
He, too, recognized the name because he said that she had been a problem for him.
She'd been over to him complaining about her not being able to be in the band, the official

drill team and the Ross volunteers and being the last one and hearing the hissing everybody in the audience was kind of looking at the stage and getting their notes together and everything so there's more attention and as I recall she took the diploma with her right hand by error moved it to her left and then put out her hand and Dr. Miller said something to her

about not shaking her hand, and she turned to Lacey and said something to him, and he said something polite to her, and as I recall, Don Carter said something like, ma'am, would you keep the line moving?
All right, did you hear anybody after this on the stage or in the Letterman's Lounge offer any comment about what had happened?
I don't recall any comments about the thing.
No, that's...
It's a long path.
I don't remember.
I do remember the fact that he didn't shake her hand, but that's really all I remember about him.
I think I remember a couple of board members saying, serves her right, you know, and I wouldn't have shaken her hand either.
All right.
When did you hear that Dr. Miller's term as president had been ended?
And how did you hear about it?
Do you remember?
Don't recall.
Okay.
Right.
Then the new interim president from engineering, were there any changes for y'all?
No.
Okay.
Things went right on.
All right.
Then in 81, Dr. Vandiver becomes president.
Any changes there?
And I say no changes.
What year?
No, there wasn't any changes then.
Okay.
And then go on forward.
Well, as all I recall, as we go on forward, we get tighter and tighter as far as numbers are concerned.
And then they begin to talk about limiting enrollment and those kinds of things.
All right.
As the limitation becomes tighter, do the number of appeals increase?
Oh, yeah, I think so.
Mm-hmm.
And did y'all make more exceptions for admissions?
Or was the number still pretty small?
I really don't remember about the numbers that we made.
What we, again, what we went through as we began to get tighter and tighter, we went to this process of changing the admission requirements.

And then at that time, the automatics and the review, and of course the review, we put the number of reviews in that we thought would give us, we had basically, we were running somewhere around 63% or something like that, so we had made it about 10,000.
If you admit about 10,000, you can expect 63,000, 6,000, somewhere in there to show up on the thing.
Did that change through the years much?
As far as I know, when I left, we were still trying for 6,000, and I think they're still keeping that 6,000 figure.
But that 63%?
Yeah, it kept eating up.
The show-up rate did?
Well, the show rate varied.
We put around 62 to 63 or 64 percent.
So we kind of worked it around that is the number that we would admit.
As far as you know, was that very unusual, that percentage?
compared to Austin or other selective public universities?
I don't know.
I don't have it prepared.

it's probably unusual to a lot of the universities because they just it's students either they know more where they're going to go all right but of course we had a lot of students that would apply to a m to texas and texas tech and you know they get admitted to all three and then they decide where they want to go based on whatever factors students decide on but
We probably did have more appeals, because we let them do written appeals, too.
We had hundreds of written appeals, which we would read through and try to make a decision as to whether we thought they were married here and making an exception or not.
The review process, it was fairly easy to take a good number in the review, and then we got tighter and tighter as we got near this maximum number that we wanted to admit.
Back to this perfect admissions process we were talking about a while ago.
What part, if any, in the review of a marginal student, what part, if any, should it play if this is the child of an A&M graduate?
We factored in a very
We were using a number on a review process.
So that would be a plus?
It was a plus, yeah.
It was a plus.
What if they lived out of state but were still an A&M graduate child?
As I recall, we were, as far as the admission process was concerned, we were treating the out-of-state son or daughter of a former student the same as we would if they were in-state.
That may be wrong, but that's the way I recall we were doing it.
All right.
Then for admission, pure and simple, was it easier for a Texas resident to be admitted than an out-of-stater?
Yeah.
Did you all have a kind of a percentage in mind of what percentage of out-of-staters you would admit?
Not really.
And again, as I recall...
The figure ran maybe around somewhere around 10%, but I may be wrong on that.
The percentage of freshmen that entered were, you know, they were predominantly Texans.
And I don't know whether that figure was 85% or what it was, but it was high.
All right.
But did I have to admit, if I'm an Oklahoman, did I have to have a slightly higher
quality performance in high school and test scores than if I lived in Dallas.
Seemed like we did.
Any unusual difficulties with international admissions?
We handled those separately and we set kind of a level on those that we would admit.
We didn't get a whole lot of applications from undergraduates.
Most of our international students were graduate students.

All right, now, through the calendar year, take me through the calendar year as to what the work schedule was for y'all, because there must have been a heavier workload at some parts of the year than others.
Let me go back to one thing on the international students.
We tried to get a representative
base from that so that we didn't get everybody from Mexico, everybody from Canada, what have you.
So we did try with the numbers there and we had exceptions to make possible.
We might be more willing to make an exception from a country who had a smaller student population from that.
Workload, of course the workload really starts
in the fall whenever they started going and making high school visits.
When we first started, we did the high school visits from the admissions office.
In fact, Gale Wood was the man to make it, and we used faculty members.
I remember Roger Feldman used to work with us quite a bit on it.
And we had other faculty members that we would call on to make a night here, a night there, when Gale just had so many.
Because sometimes we'd have two and three a night, and he couldn't make them all.
I would make a lot of them as well.
And then we got to the point where we had, and then we started hiring admissions counselors.
We developed an admissions counselor section, I think, in which we had people who only did that kind of work, which took the work off again.
This was in the mid-'80s, I guess.
He did it for a number of years all by himself, frankly.
Anyway, the workload starts in the fall.
When you start making a high school college night, we start putting out applications and they start coming in.
And eventually we put a deadline on applications when they had to be in to be considered for the following year.
And I think that it's March 1st, but I may be wrong on that.
Again, going back when I first came, we were taking applications in August.
admitting students, and students were enrolling in September.
Then we moved it up to about October, excuse me, we moved it to first of June, something like that, and then we moved it back to the first of March, I believe it is.
So the workload, it just gradually builds up.
Of course, you continue getting test scores in during that time where you can make
a decision.
We started going from the seventh semester I think to a sixth semester transcript too.
If you waited until seven you could not possibly get all the work done so we were using the
transcript, and it just slowly builds up, so to speak, till you get to the deadline, which was March the 1st.
By that time, you've got all the applications in.
You've already admitted a lot of the students, but then your review process,
in the later years didn't kick in until March 1st.
And that's when you started having to go through all of the reviews of the students who didn't meet the requirements.
And they could write in and ask to have their application reviewed, I believe it was a procedure we used on them.
I don't know what they're using now.
What recruitment processes did we use then in terms of activities and mailings and so forth?
Went to high school career?
A couple.
We went to high school, what's called college nights.
Some of them called them career days, this kind of thing.
Some of the kinds, sometimes the junior college would combine it with the high school.
Most of the time the junior college or community college did their separately.
We did that.

We had a open house or something there at the university where, I think it was generally in the fall and generally on the football weekend as I recall, where all of the colleges had open house invited students in, which was a big recruiting tool on that.
I think eventually we moved that to the spring, I believe.
But a lot of the colleges would send representatives out to high schools to talk to students and do that.

We had the former students often would have representatives in the areas and they would have functions of some kind to acquaint students with A&M and the admission requirements and so forth and this kind of thing.
When do the best students get serious about making their decisions about when and where they're going to go to college?
I think that the better students now will get their applications in early because they know that they can go ahead and get admitted and they may apply to four or five different schools.
It isn't a part of the problem.
We may have cut that down some when we put in an application fee.
They may not apply as many.
They've got to put an application fee into every school they go to.
But for some students, that's not a problem at all.
But I think they apply earlier, generally.
I have the impression that the spring of their junior year,
And by the end of the fall of their senior year, they've decided probably pretty close.

Most often, if we lost students, I'm using the word lost in quotation marks now, a student that had multiple applications and multiple admissions, usually we were up against UT Austin more often than anybody else?
I would think so.
I think they were our biggest competitor.
But seldom to the private schools?
Yeah.
Because I think those who, I think if they want to go to a private school, they probably don't want to apply to anybody else.
I may be wrong, but I think he was generally, he was against the University of Texas, possibly Texas Tech, but generally that would be from somebody out in West Texas.
What did we do, did we do anything that didn't work with recruitment?
things that in hindsight, no, that one fizzled out, didn't work?
I don't know that we did anything that just didn't work.
I mean, obviously, we never got the number of National Merit Scholars we wanted.
Well, nobody gets it.
Nobody gets it.
That's right.
Nobody gets it.
And I think we had some good programs to attract them.
Let's jump on that.
Why did our number get as high as it did?
We did a good job, and we're in the top ten still.
Yeah.
Why?
How?
It
It's my feeling, and several, I guess.
I think that we've done a better job of letting students know what kind of program we've got.
We've done a better job of recruiting because, I mean, they've developed a program.
We've brought them in and let them see just like you would a football athlete or an athlete.
And I guess third, I think we started kicking the money in.
The university did because, as I understand it,
national merit scholarships that are sponsored by industry and those that are sponsored by the schools.
And the schools can do as many as they want to, as I understand it.
And when we started putting that money in, then we had more money to give scholarships.
And of course, that's why Rice gets so many.
They've got a foundation, which they can give a lot.
The University of Texas has got a foundation, which they can give a lot.
So I think that's where the big increase in the national merit enrollees has come from.
We don't have them anymore that are getting those
quote, out of state, I guess, from industry that may be coming in, although we're probably attracting more.
But I think we've got it because the university got into the battle, if you will, with money.
Let's see.
Chronologically, we were Vandiver.
The presidents who succeeded him was...
